'''Michael "Mike" Fleisher''' ([[November 1]], [[1940s#1942|1942]] - [[February 2]], [[2018]]) is an American comic book writer who wrote one issue of the [[Star Wars (1977)|''Marvel Star Wars'']] series.

==Biography==
He came to the attention of Joe Orlando while working on comic book encyclopedias and subsequently got solid work throughout the seventies and eighties. After a failed lawsuit he worked for [[Wikipedia:2000 AD (comic)|''2000 AD'']] for a number of years in the early nineties before largely leaving the industry.

He is probably best known for writing [[Wikipedia:DC Comics|DC's]] [[Wikipedia:Jonah Hex|Jonah Hex]] character for more than a dozen years, first beginning in [[1974]] in [[Wikipedia:Weird Western Tales|''Weird Western Tales'']] (taking over from the character's creator, John Albano), then from [[1977]]-[[1985]] in his own, self-titled comic, with a series set in the character's original [[Wikipedia:Western (genre)|wild west]] setting and then in the ''Hex'' series ([[1985]]-[[1987]]) which transported the character into a post-[[Wikipedia:World War III|World War III]] setting, making him the lead in a sci-fi feature, following the events of the [[Wikipedia:Crisis on Infinite Earths|''Crisis on Infinite Earths'']] limited series. His brief run for the same company on [[Wikipedia:The Spectre|The Spectre]] with artist Jim Aparo in [[Wikipedia:Adventure Comics|''Adventure Comics'']] is, however, probably his best known work having attracted attention for the many inventive and violent ways in which the Spectre administers retribution on wrong-doers.

Over the years he has also contributed to other titles including [[Wikipedia:Conan the Barbarian|''Conan the Barbarian'']], [[Wikipedia:Man-Thing|''Man-Thing'']] and a comic series based on the role-playing game [[Wikipedia:Dungeons & Dragons|''Advanced Dungeons & Dragons'']].

